 From the 1905 Russian revolution through World War One and the long prologue to the Holocaust, the sweep of world history and the fate of this dynamic center of Jewish life were intertwined. Pinsk's role in the bloody aftermath of World War One is still the subject of scholarly debates: the murder of 35 Jewish men from Pinsk, many from its educated elite, provoked the American and British leaders to send emissaries to Pinsk. Shohet argues that the executions were a deliberate ploy by the Polish military and government to intimidate the Jewish population of the new Poland. Despite an increasingly hostile Polish state, Pinsk's Jews managed to maintain their community through the 1920s and 30s-until World War Two brought a grim Soviet interregnum succeeded by the entry of the Nazis on July 4th, 1941. For the first volume of this two-volume collection, see The Jews of Pinsk, 1506-1880.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aJewsxEducationzBelaruszPinskxHistory. 0aJewszBelaruszPinskxEconomic conditions. 0aJewszBelaruszPinskxHistory. 0aJewszBelaruszPinskxSocial conditions. 7aHISTORY / Jewish.2bisacsh1 aMirsky, Mark Jay, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aRosman, Moshe, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aTropper, Faigie08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780804785020zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804785020423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804785020.jpg  a978-3-11-070420-4  SUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles